[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] In computer programming, **boilerplate code**, or simply **boilerplate**, are sections of code that are repeated in multiple places with little to no variation.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] When using languages that are considered *verbose*, the programmer must write a lot of boilerplate code to accomplish only minor functionality.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] It is also possible to move boilerplate code to an *abstract class* so that it can be inherited by any number of *concrete classes*.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] Another option would be to move it into a subroutine so that it can be called instead of being duplicated.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] The term arose from the newspaper business.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] Columns and other pieces that were distributed by print syndicates were sent to subscribing newspapers in the form of prepared printing plates.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] Because of their resemblance to the metal plates used in the making of boilers, they became known as "boiler plates", and their resulting text—"boilerplate text".
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] As the stories that were distributed by boiler plates were usually "fillers" rather than "serious" news, the term became synonymous with unoriginal, repeated text.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] A related term is *bookkeeping code*, referring to code that is not part of the business logic but is interleaved with it in order to keep data structures updated or handle secondary aspects of the program.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] One form of boilerplate consists of declarations which, while not part of the program logic or the language's essential syntax, are added to the start of a source file as a matter of custom.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] The first line is a shebang, which identifies the file as a Perl script that can be executed directly on the command line on Unix/Linux systems.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] The other two are pragmas turning on warnings and strict mode, which are mandated by fashionable Perl programming style.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] This next example is a C/C++ programming language boilerplate, `#include` guard.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] This checks, and sets up, a global flag to tell the compiler whether the file myinterface.h has already been included.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] As many interdepending files may be involved in the compilation of a module, this avoids processing the same header multiple times, (which would lead to errors due to multiple definitions with the same name).
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] In Java programs, DTO classes are often provided with methods for getting and setting instance variables.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] The definitions of these methods can frequently be regarded as boilerplate.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] Although the code will vary from one class to another, it is sufficiently stereotypical in structure that it would be better generated automatically than written by hand.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] Most of the boilerplate in this example exists to fulfill requirements of JavaBeans.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] If the variables **name** and **owner** were declared as public, the accessor and mutator methods would not be needed.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] In Java 14, record classes were added to fight with this issue.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] To reduce the amount of boilerplate, many frameworks have been developed, e.g.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] In some other programming languages it may be possible to achieve the same thing with less boilerplate, when the language has built-in support for such common constructs.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] The WHATWG HTML Living Standard defines that the `<html>`, `<head>` and `<body>` tags may be safely omitted under most circumstances.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] The `<meta charset="UTF-8">` tag is technically redundant when coming directly from a web server configured to send the character encoding in an HTTP header, though it becomes useful when the HTML response is saved in an `.html` file, cache, or web archive.
[src:lombok-java-lib/boilerplate-code] Google's HTML/CSS style guide recommends that all optional tags be omitted, resulting in much less boilerplate.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] In computing, **code generation** is part of the process chain of a compiler, in which an intermediate representation of source code is converted into a form (e.g., machine code) that the target system can readily execute.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] Sophisticated compilers typically perform multiple passes over various intermediate forms.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] This multi-stage process is used because many algorithms for code optimization are easier to apply one at a time, or because the input to one optimization relies on the completed processing performed by another optimization.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] This organization also facilitates the creation of a single compiler that can target multiple architectures, as only the last of the code generation stages (the *backend*) needs to change from target to target.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] The input to the code generator typically consists of a parse tree or an abstract syntax tree.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] The tree is converted into a linear sequence of instructions, usually in an intermediate language such as three-address code.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] Further stages of compilation may or may not be referred to as "code generation", depending on whether they involve a significant change in the representation of the program.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] In addition to converting an intermediate representation into a linear sequence of machine instructions, a typical code generator tries to optimize the generated code.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] In a compiler that uses an intermediate language, there may be two instruction selection stages—one to convert the parse tree into intermediate code, and a second phase, much later, to convert the intermediate code into instructions from the instruction set of the target machine.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] This second phase does not require a tree traversal; it can be done linearly, and typically involves a simple replacement of intermediate-language operations with their corresponding opcodes.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] However, suppose the compiler is a language translator (for example, one that converts Java to C++).
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] In that case, the second code-generation phase may involve *building* a tree from the linear intermediate code.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] When code generation occurs at runtime, as in just-in-time compilation (JIT), the entire process must be efficient with respect to space and time.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] For example, when regular expressions are interpreted and used to generate code at runtime, a non-deterministic finite-state machine is often generated instead of a deterministic one because the former can usually be created more quickly and occupies less memory space than the latter.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] Despite generally generating less efficient code, JIT code generation can take advantage of profiling information that is available only at runtime.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] The fundamental task of taking input in one language and producing output in a non-trivially different language can be understood in terms of the core transformational operations of formal language theory.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] Consequently, some techniques initially developed for use in compilers have come to be employed in other ways.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] For example, YACC (Yet Another Compiler-Compiler) takes input in Backus–Naur form and converts it to a parser in C.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] Though it was initially created for automatic generation of a parser for a compiler, yacc is also often used to automate writing code that needs to be modified each time specifications are changed.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] Many integrated development environments (IDEs) support some form of automatic source-code generation, often using algorithms in common with compiler code generators, although commonly less complicated.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] In general, a syntax and semantic analyzer tries to retrieve the program's structure from the source code, while a code generator uses this structural information (e.g., data types) to produce code.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] In other words, the former *adds* information while the latter *loses* some.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] One consequence of this information loss is that reflection becomes difficult or even impossible.
[src:lombok-java-lib/code-generation-compiler] To counter this problem, code generators often embed syntactic and semantic information and the code necessary for execution.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] In the Java computer programming language, an **annotation** is a form of syntactic metadata that can be added to Java source code, like an attribute.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] Classes, methods, variables, parameters and Java packages may be annotated.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] Like Javadoc tags, Java annotations can be read from source files.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] Unlike Javadoc tags, Java annotations can also be embedded in and read from Java class files generated by the Java compiler.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] This allows annotations to be retained by the Java virtual machine at run-time and read via reflection.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] It is possible to create meta-annotations out of the existing ones in Java.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] The Java platform has various *ad-hoc* annotation mechanisms—for example, the *`transient`* modifier, or the *`@Deprecated`* javadoc tag.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] The Java Specification Request JSR-175 introduced the general-purpose annotation (also known as *metadata*) facility to the Java Community Process in 2002; it gained approval in September 2004.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] Annotations became available in the language itself beginning with version 1.5 of the Java Development Kit (JDK).
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] The `apt` tool provided a provisional interface for compile-time annotation processing in JDK version 1.5; JSR-269 formalized this, and it became integrated into the javac compiler in version 1.6.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] In C++26, C++ added annotations for reflection that are similar to Java annotations.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] Java defines a set of annotations that are built into the language.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] Of the seven standard annotations, three are part of java.lang, and the remaining four are imported from `java.lang.annotation`.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] There was previously an annotation, `@ManagedBean`, located in `jakarta.annotation`, which was historically used to declare a Managed Bean which are container managed objects that support a small set of basic services such as resource injection, lifecycle callbacks and interceptors.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] This example demonstrates the use of the `@Override` annotation.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] It instructs the compiler to check parent classes for matching methods.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] In this case, an error is generated because the `gettype()` method of class Cat doesn't in fact override `getType()` of class Animal like is desired, because of the mismatching case.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] If the `@Override` annotation were absent, a new method of name `gettype()` would be created in class Cat.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] Annotation type declarations are similar to normal interface declarations.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] An at-sign (@) precedes the keyword "interface".
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] Annotations may include a set of key-value pairs, which are modeled as methods of the annotation type.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] Each method declaration defines an element of the annotation type.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] Method declarations must not have any parameters or a throws clause.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] Return types are restricted to primitives, String, Class, enums, annotations, and arrays of the preceding types.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] The compiler reserves a set of special annotations (including `@Deprecated`, `@Override` and `@SuppressWarnings`) for syntactic purposes.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] Annotations are widely used by frameworks as a way of conveniently applying behaviors to user-defined classes and methods that must otherwise be declared in an external source (such as an XML configuration file) or programmatically (with API calls).
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] For instance, the library *Project Lombok* makes extensive usage of annotations to reduce boilerplate.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] The annotations are not method calls and will not, by themselves, do anything.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] Rather, the class object is passed to the Jakarta Persistence implementation at run-time, which then extracts the annotations to generate an object–relational mapping.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] When Java source code is compiled, annotations can be processed by compiler plug-ins called annotation processors.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] Processors can produce informational messages or create additional Java source files or resources, which in turn may be compiled and processed.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] However, annotation processors cannot modify the annotated code itself.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] (Code modifications may be implemented using methods beyond the Java Language Specification.) The Java compiler conditionally stores annotation metadata in the class files, if the annotation has a `RetentionPolicy` of `CLASS` or `RUNTIME`.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] Later, the JVM or other programs can look for the metadata to determine how to interact with the program elements or change their behavior.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] In addition to processing an annotation using an annotation processor, a Java programmer can write their own code that uses reflection to process the annotation.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] Java SE 5 supports a new interface that is defined in the `java.lang.reflect` package.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] This package contains the interface called `AnnotatedElement` that is implemented by the Java reflection classes including `Class`, `Constructor`, `Field`, `Method`, and `Package`.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] The implementations of this interface are used to represent an annotated element of the program currently running in the Java Virtual Machine.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] This interface allows annotations to be read reflectively.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] The `AnnotatedElement` interface provides access to annotations having `RUNTIME` retention.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] This access is provided by the `getAnnotation`, `getAnnotations`, and `isAnnotationPresent` methods.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] Because annotation types are compiled and stored in byte code files just like classes, the annotations returned by these methods can be queried just like any regular Java object.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-annotation] Libraries such as JUnit use annotation processing to generate unit tests.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java gained popularity shortly after its release, and has been a popular programming language since then.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java was the third most popular programming language in 2022 according to GitHub.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] Although still widely popular, there has been a gradual decline in use of Java in recent years with other languages using JVM gaining popularity.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java was designed by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] It was released in May 1995 as a core component of Sun's Java platform.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] The original and reference implementation Java compilers, virtual machines (VMs), and class libraries were released by Sun under proprietary licenses.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] As of May 2007, in compliance with the specifications of the Java Community Process, Sun had relicensed most of its Java technologies under the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] Oracle, which bought Sun in 2010, offers its own HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] However, the official reference implementation is the OpenJDK JVM, which is open-source software used by most developers and is the default JVM for almost all Linux distributions.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] As of March 2026, Java 26 is the current version.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] James Gosling, Mike Sheridan, and Patrick Naughton initiated the Java language project in June 1991.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java was originally designed for interactive television, but it was too advanced for the digital cable television industry at the time.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] The language was initially called *Oak* after an oak tree that stood outside Gosling's office.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] Later the project went by the name *Green* and was finally renamed *Java*, from Java coffee, a type of coffee from Indonesia.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] Gosling designed Java with a C/C++-style syntax that system and application programmers would find familiar.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] Sun Microsystems released the first public implementation as Java 1.0 in 1996.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] It promised write once, run anywhere (WORA) functionality, providing no-cost run-times on popular platforms.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] Fairly secure and featuring configurable security, it allowed network- and file-access restrictions.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] Major web browsers soon incorporated the ability to run Java applets within web pages, and Java quickly became popular.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] The Java 1.0 compiler was re-written in Java by Arthur van Hoff to comply strictly with the Java 1.0 language specification.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] With the advent of Java 2 (released initially as J2SE 1.2 in December 1998 – 1999), new versions had multiple configurations built for different types of platforms.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] J2EE included technologies and APIs for enterprise applications typically run in server environments, while J2ME featured APIs optimized for mobile applications.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] In 2006, for marketing purposes, Sun renamed new J2 versions as *Java EE*, *Java ME*, and *Java SE*, respectively.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] In 1997, Sun Microsystems approached the ISO/IEC JTC 1 standards body and later the Ecma International to formalize Java, but it soon withdrew from the process.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java remains a *de facto* standard, controlled through the Java Community Process.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] At one time, Sun made most of its Java implementations available without charge, despite their proprietary software status.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] Sun generated revenue from Java through the selling of licenses for specialized products such as the Java Enterprise System.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] On November 13, 2006, Sun released much of its Java virtual machine (JVM) as free and open-source software (FOSS), under the terms of the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] On May 8, 2007, Sun finished the process, making all of its JVM's core code available under free software/open-source distribution terms, aside from a small portion of code to which Sun did not hold the copyright.
[src:lombok-java-lib/java-programming-language] Sun's vice-president Rich Green said that Sun's ideal role with regard to Java was as an *evangelist*.
